Reth by Paradigm has been getting quite alot of attention lately- but why?

What exactly is Reth? How does it compare to more traditional ETH clients like Erigon and Geth?

Let's jump into it ðŸ§µ â†“

(Planning to post this on Twitter later this week, wanted to post it here first. btw, are threads a "thing" here?):

ðŸ”Ž First, we need to understand what exactly Reth is:

Reth (Rust Ethereum) is, in short, a client for Ethereum similar in principal to clients like Geth and Erigon

Although Reth, due in part to the fact that it's made with Rust, stands out as an incredibly efficient alternative.

To expand a bit futher:

Reth specifically excels in a few key areas:
â€¢ Performance, as mentioned - leveraging Rust to achieve this
â€¢ Modularity - through organizing components into individual libraries
â€¢ Configurability - self explanatory

Currently, most nodes use Geth for full nodes, with Erigon often preferred for archive nodes.

Geth (Go Ethereum) is, as you'd expect, written in Go â›“ï¸ 

While the most popular implementation, it's not the most efficient.
â€¢ ~14.8TB Archival nodes
â€¢ Computationally expensive

ðŸ“ The inefficiency with Geth on Archive nodes has warranted a number of solutions over the years.

Erigon is the most popular of these solutions through it's variety of disk optimizations and syncing strategies.

This means that Erigon can run Archive nodes with ~3.5TB ðŸ—ƒï¸

ðŸ“„ But even Erigon doesn't beat Reth (Geth is out of the question at this point when it comes to efficiency).

Reth takes only ~2TB of storage for archive nodes; this is a huge step in the right direction for node accessibility and general weight.

Beyond the size optimizations, Reth makes alot of general performance strides.

For example, i2huer and troublor (on Twitter) ran some tests earlier this week and observed a nearly 4.4x improvement in complicated transaction simulation when using Reth.

https://twitter.com/i2huer/status/1668329972866625537

ðŸ› ï¸ Okay- we know that Reth is performant and size-efficient, but what about the modularity and configurability piece?

Let's touch on configurability first.

Reth, as mentioned, has maintained a focus on being as configurable as possible in an effort to meet a variety of usecases.

ðŸ—ï¸ Modularity- one of my personal favorites.

Reth also enables a high-degree of intrinsic modularity through building each major component of Reth to be used as a library.

Components like:
â€¢ Storage
â€¢ Networking
â€¢ Consensus
â€¢ Execution
â€¢ Sync
â€¢ RPC
â€¢ Payloads

ðŸ¦€ Reth is not complete- in fact they encourage continued use of Geth, primarily for it's stability and ecosystem-wide support.

But, Reth is undoubtedly an exciting evolution in Ethereum clients and will continue making strides throughout the ecosystem as it improves.
